{{Infobox building | name = Takayama Uichi Memorial Museum of Art | native_name = 七戸町立鷹山宇一記念美術館 | image = | caption = | cost = | owner = | address = 67-94 Arakumanai | location_town = [[Shichinohe, Aomori|Shichinohe]], [[Aomori Prefecture]] | location_country = [[Japan]] | coordinates = {{coord|40.716934|N|141.155972|E|display=title,inline|format=dms|type:landmark_region:JP_scale:10000}} | opened_date = 1 August 1994 | inauguration_date = | renovation_date = | demolition_date = | destruction_date = | other_dimensions = | floor_count = | floor_area = | architect = | architecture_firm = | url = {{homepage|http://www.takayamamuseum.jp}} }}
{{nihongo|'''Takayama Uichi Memorial Museum of Art'''|七戸町立鷹山宇一記念美術館|Shichinohe chōritsu Takayama Uichi kinen bijutsukan}} opened in [[Shichinohe, Aomori|Shichinohe]], [[Aomori Prefecture]], Japan, in 1994. The collection comprises four main areas: three rooms with paintings by four artists from or otherwise associated with Shichinohe, namely {{nihongo|Takayama Uichi|鷹山宇一}} (1908–1999) and fellow [[yōga]] artist {{nihongo|Hirano Shirō|平野四郎}} (1904–1983), [[Nihonga]] artist {{nihongo|Toya Banzan|鳥谷幡山}} (1876–1966), and {{nihongo|Kamiizumi Kayō|上泉華陽}} (1892–1979), who specialised in painting horses; the Lamp Hall, with its nucleus in Takayama Uichi's collection of nineteenth-century western and [[Meiji period|Meiji]] lamps; the Ema Hall, with folk artefacts centred upon [[Ema (Shinto)|ema]], [[hagoita]], and other related items from nearby {{nihongo|Mirumachi Kannon-dō|見町観音堂}} and {{nihongo|Kodako Fudō-dō|小田子不動堂}} that have been [[Cultural Properties of Japan|designated]] [[Important Tangible Folk Cultural Properties]]; and a Spanish Folk Ceramic Hall.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.takayamamuseum.jp/collection/display/display1/ |script-title=ja:展示作品 |trans-title=Works Displayed |language=Japanese |publisher=Takayama Uichi Memorial Museum of Art |accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bunka.go.jp/bsys/maindetails.asp?register_id=301&item_id=7 |script-title=ja:南部七戸見町観音堂庶民信仰資料 |trans-title=Artefacts relating to the Faith of the People at Mirumachi Kannon-dō, Shichinohe |language=Japanese |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bunka.go.jp/bsys/maindetails.asp?register_id=301&item_id=8 |script-title=ja:南部七戸小田子不動堂奉納絵馬 |trans-title=Ema Dedicated at Kodako Fudō-dō, Shichinohe |language=Japanese |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pref.aomori.lg.jp/bunka/education/kennaihakubutukan_itiran.html |script-title=ja:青森県内博物館等施設一覧 |trans-title=List of Museums in Aomori Prefecture |language=Japanese |publisher=[[Aomori Prefecture]] |accessdate=16 October 2015}}</ref>
